#. Tag: title
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:9
#, no-c-format
msgid "SELinux"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:11
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This chapter gives a brief overview of SELinux implementation on &slema;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:16
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"SELinux was developed as an additional Linux security solution that uses the "
"security framework in the Linux kernel. The purpose was to allow for a more "
"granular security policy that goes beyond the standard Discretionary Access "
"Controls (DAC), the traditional file permissions of owner/group/world, and "
"read/write/execute."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:23
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"SELinux uses labels attached to objects (for example, files and network "
"sockets) and uses them for access decisions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:27
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The default action of SELinux is to deny any access. SELinux allows only "
"actions that were specifically allowed in the SELinux policy. Another "
"feature of SELinux that increases security is that SELinux allows strict "
"confinement of processes up to the point where the processes cannot access "
"files of other processes on the same system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:34
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"SELinux was designed to enhance existing security solutions, not to replace "
"them. For example, discretionary access control (DAC) is still applied even "
"if the system is using SELinux. If DAC denies access first, SELinux is then "
"not used as the access was already blocked by another mechanism."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:41
#, no-c-format
msgid "Getting SELinux"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:42
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"SELinux is installed by default when installing &slema; by &yast; or is part "
"of the pre-built images. The default mode is set to enforced on all "
"deployment types, and the file system is labelled."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:47
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If in any case SELinux is not set up on your system, run the following "
"command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:50
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;transactional-update setup-selinux"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:51
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Reboot your system after the command has finished. The command installs the "
"SELinux policy if it is not installed, sets the <literal>enforcing</literal> "
"SELinux mode and rebuilds <literal>initramfs</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:58
#, no-c-format
msgid "SELinux modes"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:59
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"SELinux can run in one of three modes: <literal>disabled</literal> , "
"<literal>permissive</literal> , or <literal>enforcing</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:63
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Using the <literal>disabled</literal> mode means that no rules from the "
"SELinux policy are applied and your system is not protected. Therefore, the "
"<literal>disabled</literal> mode is not recommended."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:68
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In the <literal>permissive</literal> mode, SELinux is active, the security "
"policy is loaded, the file system is labeled and access denial entries are "
"logged. However, the policy is not enforced and thus no access is actually "
"denied."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:74
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In the <literal>enforced</literal> mode, the security policy is applied. "
"Each access that is not explicitly allowed by the policy is denied."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:78
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can switch between the <literal>enforcing</literal> and "
"<literal>permissive</literal> modes by using the <command>setenforce</"
"command> command. Alternatively, you can switch between all SELinux modes by "
"editing the <filename>/etc/selinux/config</filename> configuration file. "
"Changes performed by the <command>setenforce</command> command are valid "
"only until the next reboot. For persistent changes of the SELinux mode, edit "
"the <filename>/etc/selinux/config</filename> configuration file."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:88
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <command>setenforce</command> command has the following syntax:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:91
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;setenforce <replaceable>MODE_ID</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:92
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"where <replaceable>MODE_ID</replaceable> is <replaceable>0</replaceable> for "
"the <literal>permissive</literal> mode or <replaceable>1</replaceable> for "
"the <literal>enforced</literal> mode."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:97
#, no-c-format
msgid "To verify the mode, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:100
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;getenforce"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:101
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The command should return <literal>permissive</literal> or "
"<literal>enforced</literal> , depending on the provided "
"<replaceable>MODE_ID</replaceable> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:106
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To change the SELinux mode permanently, in the file <filename>/etc/selinux/"
"config</filename> , change the value of <literal>SELINUX</literal> to "
"<literal>disabled</literal> , or <literal>permissive</literal> , or "
"<literal>enforced</literal> as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:112
#, no-c-format
msgid "SELINUX=disabled"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:113
#, no-c-format
msgid "The changes in the file are applied after the next reboot."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:117
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Relabeling your system after switching from the <literal>disabled</literal> "
"mode"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:118
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you disable SELinux on your system and then enable it later, make sure "
"that you relabel your system. When SELinux is disabled, and you perform "
"changes to your file system, the changes are not reflected in the context "
"anymore (for example, new files do not have any context). Therefore, you "
"need to relabel your system by using the <command>restorecon</command> "
"command, using the <literal>autorelabel</literal> boot parameter, or by "
"creating a file that will trigger relabeling on the next boot. To create the "
"file, run the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:128
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;touch /etc/selinux/.autorelabel"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:129
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"After reboot, the file <filename>/etc/selinux/.autorelabel</filename> is "
"replaced with another flag file: <filename>/etc/selinux/.relabelled</"
"filename> to prevent relabeling on subsequent reboots."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:138
#, no-c-format
msgid "SELinux policy overview"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:139
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The policy is the key component in SELinux. Your SELinux policy defines "
"rules that specify which objects can access which files, directories, ports, "
"and processes on a system. To do this, a security context is defined for all "
"of these."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:145
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"An SELinux policy contains a huge number of rules. To make it more "
"manageable, policies are often split into modules. This allows the "
"administrator to switch protection on or off for different parts of the "
"system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:151
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"When compiling the policy for your system, you will have a choice to either "
"work with a modular policy, or a monolithic policy, where one huge policy is "
"used to protect everything on your system. It is strongly recommended to use "
"a modular policy and not a monolithic policy. Modular policies are much "
"easier to manage."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:158
#, no-c-format
msgid "&slema; is shipped with the <literal>targeted</literal> SELinux policy."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:162
#, no-c-format
msgid "Creating policies for containers"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:163
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&productnameshort; is delivered with a policy that by default does not allow "
"containers to access files outside of the container data. On the other hand, "
"all network access is allowed. Typically, containers are created with bind "
"mounts and should be able to access other directories like, for example, "
"<filename>/home</filename> or <filename>/var</filename> . You may want a "
"possibility to allow access to these directories or, on the contrary, "
"restrict some ports to the container even if SELinux is used on your system. "
"In this case, you need to create new policy rules that enable or disable the "
"access. &productnameshort; provides the Udica tool for this purpose."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:175
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The following procedure describes how to create a custom policy for your "
"containers:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:181
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Make sure that SELinux is in the enforcing mode. For details, refer to <xref "
"linkend=\"sec-switching-modes\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:187
#, no-c-format
msgid "Start a container using the following parameters:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:190
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.root;podman run -v /home:/home:rw -v /var/:/var/:rw -p 21:21 -it "
"sle15 bash"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:191
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The container runs with the default policy that does not allow access to the "
"mount points but does not restrict other ports."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:197
#, no-c-format
msgid "You can exit the container."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:202
#, no-c-format
msgid "Obtain the container ID:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:205
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.root;podman ps -a\n"
"\n"
"CONTAINER ID  "
"IMAGE                                                                              "
"COMMAND     CREATED        STATUS            PORTS               NAMES\n"
"e59f9d0f86f2  registry.opensuse.org/devel/bci/tumbleweed/containerfile/"
"opensuse/bci/ruby:latest  /bin/bash   8 minutes ago  Up 8 seconds ago  "
"0.0.0.0:21-&gt;21/tcp  zen_ramanujan\n"
"        "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:212
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Create a JSON file that Udica will use to create a custom policy for the "
"container:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:216
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.root;podman inspect e59f9d0f86f2 &gt; <replaceable>OUTPUT_JSON_FILE</"
"replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:217
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For example, substitute <replaceable>OUTPUT_JSON_FILE</replaceable> with "
"<filename>container.json</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:223
#, no-c-format
msgid "Run Udica to generate a policy according to the container parameters:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:226
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.root;udica -j <replaceable>OUTPUT_JSON_FILE</replaceable>  "
"<replaceable>CUSTOM_CONTAINER_POLICY</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:227
#, no-c-format
msgid "For example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:230
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;udica -j container.json custom_policy"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:233
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"According to the provided instructions, load the policy modules by running:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:237
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.root;semodule -i custom_policy.cil /usr/share/udica/templates/"
"{base_container.cil,net_container.cil,home_container.cil}"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:240
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Run a container with the new policy module by using the <option>--security-"
"opt</option> option as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:244
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.root;podman run --security-opt label=type:custom_policy.process -v /"
"home:/home:rw -v /var/:/var/:rw -p 21:21 -it sle15 bash"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:250
#, no-c-format
msgid "SELinux security context"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:251
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The security context is a set of information assigned to a file or a "
"process. It consists of SELinux user, role, type, level and category. This "
"information is used to make access control decisions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:257
#, no-c-format
msgid "SELinux context fields"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:259
#, no-c-format
msgid "SELinux user"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:261
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"is an identity defined in the policy that is authorized for a specific set "
"of roles and for a specific <emphasis>level</emphasis> range. Each Linux "
"user is mapped to an SELinux user. SELinux does not use the list of user "
"accounts maintained by Linux in <filename>/etc/passwd</filename> , but uses "
"its own database and mapping. By convention, the identity name is suffixed "
"with <literal>_u</literal> , for example: <literal>user_u</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:273
#, no-c-format
msgid "role"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:275
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"defines a set of permissions that a user can be granted. A role defines "
"which <emphasis>types</emphasis> a user assigned to this role can access. By "
"convention, the role name is suffixed with <literal>_r</literal> , for "
"example: <literal>system_r</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:284
#, no-c-format
msgid "type"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:286
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"conveys information on how particular files and processes can interact. A "
"process consists of files with a concrete SELinux type, and it cannot access "
"files outside of this type. By convention, the type name is suffixed with "
"<literal>_t</literal> , for example: <literal>var_t</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:296
#, no-c-format
msgid "level"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:298
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"is an optional attribute that specifies the range of levels of clearance in "
"the multilevel security."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:305
#, no-c-format
msgid "category"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: slemicro_security_selinux.xml:307
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"is an optional attribute that allows you to add categories to processes, "
"files, and users. A user can then access files that have the same category."
msgstr ""

